```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];
    Pendulum_Potentiometer -> Signal_Buffer -> Low_Pass_Filter -> Voltage_Scaler -> Anti_Aliasing_Filter -> DAQ_Input;
}
```

```Explanations
Pendulum_Potentiometer: This is the potentiometer attached to the pendulum. As the pendulum swings, the resistance changes linearly with the angle. The potentiometer converts the mechanical angle into an electrical signal (voltage). Given the 10kOhm value and -10 to +10 volts supply, it will output a voltage range corresponding to the angular position of the pendulum.

Signal_Buffer: The buffer's primary function is to prevent the potentiometer from being loaded by any subsequent stages. It maintains signal integrity and provides a low output impedance, making it easier to interface with the next stages of signal conditioning.

Low_Pass_Filter: This filter attenuates unwanted high-frequency noise, including the 50 and 60 Hz from power lines, to ensure a clean signal representative of the pendulum's movement. It should have a cutoff frequency below the pendulum's highest frequency of interest.

Voltage_Scaler: Since the DAQ can only accept voltages up to +/- 7 V, this stage scales down the voltage to fall within the acceptable range. It should linearly scale the voltage derived from the potentiometer to ensure accurate representation of the pendulum's angle without exceeding the DAQ's voltage limits.

Anti_Aliasing_Filter: Before the signal is digitized by the DAQ, this low-pass filter is necessary to remove any frequency components above half the sampling rate of the DAQ (Nyquist frequency), thus preventing aliasing in the digital signal.

DAQ_Input: This represents the analog input channel of the Data Acquisition System (DAQ), which will digitize the conditioned analog voltage signal corresponding to the pendulum's angular position for further processing or analysis.
```

